You have a black box in your car?
As American road planners struggle to find the money to fix the crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile driven by a motorist and relay that information to officials, are at the center of a controversial effort to modernize the outdated highway funding system of America by Washington and state planning agencies.
The usually boring arena of highway planning suddenly gave rise to intense debate and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use little boxes to track how many miles you've driven and maybe even where you've driven them - and then use that information in tax returns.
The tea party movement is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of issues regarding privacy.
And while Congress can't agree on whether to proceed, several states aren't waiting.
They're thinking about how, over the next decade, we can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have satellite tracking capabilities.
It's really necessary for our country.
"This is not an issue we can have a choice on", said Hassan Ihrat, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which is planning to start tracking the miles driven by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology for that already exists.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funding from the Government Highway Fund, which is funded by taxes Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars are doing more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't been raised in 20 years.
Politicians don't want to raise the tax even one cent with gasoline prices so high.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable", said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed 500 tracking devices on cars to test its underpayment system.
"It's the best alternative in the long run", he said.
The Zunads call it a missed user fee.
It's no wonder that this idea appeals to urban liberals, because taxes can change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California's planning authorities are looking at this system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state's ambitious global warming laws.
However, Representative Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free marketers at the Reason foundation are also excited about making drivers pay per mile.
"This is not just a tax that will go into a black hole", said Adrian Moore, Reason's vice president of policy.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. transportation secretaries who in 2011 urged Congress to move toward the wrong payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles to get to work or the city in their daily lives.
A few states and cities, however, are going their own way.
The most enthusiastic response is in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are being recruited to take part in the largest trial in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for mileage instead of gas tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project is already complete.
New York is looking into it.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes transportation departments in 17 east coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is looking at how they can make this change.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where some 50 volunteer vehicles were recently fitted with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government might be tracking their every move.
"The concern about 'big brother' and things like that is a big problem", said Alauddin Khan, chief of strategy and efficiency management for the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
As the trials were underway, the Nevada chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website: "It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices".
There is no need to build a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of individual citizens' daily movements.
Nevada is one of several states that is working hard to find a low-cost technology that would allow state authorities to keep track of driving miles without any information about time or location.
If you can do that, the Khan said, the society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to a small startup in California called True Mileage.
Originally, this company was not engaged in the collection of state taxes.
It was looking to enter the emerging market for a form of auto insurance where drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices she's testing are attracting road designers because they don't use GPS and they provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded by a modem.
"People are more likely to do this if you don't track their speed and you don't track their location", said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been some big mistakes in some of these state pilots.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can opt out altogether, choosing instead to pay a flat rate based on the average number of miles driven by all residents of the state.
Elsewhere, they're hoping to sell the idea to a wary public by making the devices do more, not less.
In New York, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxing device that would also accept payment from parking meters, provide "pay as you drive" insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists will be attracted to the benefits they will be offered", says the city's planning document.
Some transportation designers, however, are wondering if all this talk about wrongful payment is just a huge distraction.
In the San Francisco Bay Area, officials at the city's transportation commission say that Congress could very easily have overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
"There's no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take an aspirin", said Randy Rentchler, the commission's director of legislative and public affairs.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers will be concerned about their privacy and a lot of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a backup plan to provide Ukraine with gas, and to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of an association agreement between the EU and Ukraine at the Vilnius summit.
The IMF is in talks with the IMF about a standby loan, and another EU official directly involved in the talks added that they aim to have an agreement soon.
In addition to the potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine could receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts polled by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF can overcome long-standing disagreements over funding terms.
The international rating agency S&P, which on Friday downgraded Ukraine's sovereign rating by one notch to "B-" from "B", also does not believe in the possibility of reforms needed to receive aid.
However, EU officials say the IMF may be able to show flexibility in its lending terms, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the financial support plan, the EU has a backup plan for supplying Ukraine with gas, the bulk of which now comes from Russia.
It could be gas from Nord Stream or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, officials say, is the most feasible and acceptable way if Russia "isolates" Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reverse supply to Ukraine can only be used for a few weeks, and will likely lead to a decrease in supply to other regions.
"EU countries and Ukrainians are negotiating how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but by other routes", the source added.
Russia out of the fight for polluting cities with cars
Attempts to solve the transportation problems of large cities have been observed in most of the world's megacities since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about rebuilding and expanding the highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for car trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The well-known example of Singapore is that it has a strict quota for the increase in the number of private cars, and the right to buy them is bought at auctions.
It can cost two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee to enter the city centre.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where only vehicles with a certain eco-class, which also use high-quality fuel (including biofuel or electric cars) are allowed to enter.
Beijing's Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a "five-year clean air plan" in 2012 with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
As the director of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau's Transport Pollution Control Division, Li Kunsheng, told Kommersant, the five-year plan's main goal is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to a level not exceeding 6 million (currently 5.2 million), and increase fuel consumption by no more than 5% per vehicle.
According to the agency, Beijing's motor vehicles are now responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program - the restriction of the use of automobile transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
The urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include, among other things, the accelerated transition to European fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuel, the restriction of cars entering the central part of the city, the prohibition on the use of outdated vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs, the replacement of old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric transport (including public and service), the development of public transport (including high-speed).
Beijing's automotive innovations also include the ban on all private cars within the fifth transport ring (there are six in the capital of China) one day a week (the relevant information is contained in the vehicle number plate), as well as the issuance of registration marks for cars on the basis of a lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of operation of the lottery, the total number of permits for the registration of private cars in Beijing amounted to only one third of the number in 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental Protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011, "mobile sources" accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, automobile emissions are ten times those of industrial emissions, and in St. Petersburg, nine times.
In Russia, they are only just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
The director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy of the Higher School of Economics, Mikhail Blinkin, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for car trips are obviously unpopular, and can only be adopted by society if they are fully universal.
In the case of Moscow, a unique problem arises, connected with the structure of its car park, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory effects - service and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, whose total number is not less than 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of the car park of Moscow).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM Center in St. Petersburg produced a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between housing, road surface and the amount of motor vehicles.
The researchers' main findings: the city center is provided with roads twice as short as required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking lots, but car storage, not to expand, but to shorten the driving part (so that the streets become more friendly for pedestrians), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the boundaries of the protection zone of the historic center (the total area of about 3212 hectares, covering a number of central areas of the city).
