Goldman Sachs warned of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to Russia's main driver of fragile economic growth - consumption.
These are primarily the crisis of non-payment of consumer loans and the mass layoffs.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it has been driven by consumption, which has hardly slowed down", said Goldman Sachs chief economist for Russia, Clemens Graffe, presenting the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy yesterday.
Now the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
At 6% inflation, it will be able to meet future consumer demand at about its current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But Russian companies are losing profitability, so they're probably going to be optimizing their personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, explained Mr. Graf.
Companies faced a decline in profitability.
If it doesn't, it could lead to layoffs and unemployment.
Russian business cannot afford not to raise salaries, comments Vladimir Pantyushyn, chief economist for Russia and the CIS at Barclays Capital.
Unemployment is near historic lows, competition for workers is high.
To attract or retain employees, employers are forced to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is also being supported by very rapid growth in consumer credit.
According to Mr Graf, the extremely high interest rates on consumer loans do not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
"We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth in consumer credit, money is not distributed in the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments", said the economist.
But the problem is that Goldman Sachs is expecting more delinquencies on its unsecured loans.
They're mostly taken by the poor, the ones who don't have anything to put up.
Interest rates on these loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned", Mr Graffe said.
So the second threat to Russia's economic growth is a possible credit crunch.
The director of the Banking Institute of the Higher School of Economics, Vasily Solodkov, is already seeing signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, lacking access to cheap resources like state banks, were forced to raise funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went to war and started to lower interest rates, the economist continues.
Small credit unions can't lend at the same interest rate, or they'll have a negative margin.
If the state banks do not abandon dumping, Russia is threatened with a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The economic expert believes that the loss of the licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks is a harbinger of a mass collapse.
"Government banks alone will not be able to cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis", warns the head of the institute.
But consumption growth will slow down without the default crisis, the investment bank believes, because of the refusal to index civil servants and military salaries, laid out in the current draft budget.
The consumption shock will be partially mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, by lower inflation).
But only in part: if investment does not increase (and the prerequisites for this are not yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushyn of Barclays Capital does not see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios yet.
"The main risk is the continued fall in oil prices", he says.
He estimates that Russia's economy will begin to shrink if oil prices fall below $90 per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet able to lower interest rates in the economy.
The paradox is that inflation has fallen and banks have raised rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting", said Clemens Graf.
The central bank's interest rate policy does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is the end of all hope", said Clemens Graffe.
The money raised at the Central Bank auctions is used by banks to manage their liquidity, not to lend to the economy.
As soon as the rate is reduced, the exchange rate changes immediately, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
"Sooner or later the central bank will realize that this strategy is not working", Mr. Graf said, and recalled that the government plans to put the ruble into free float by the end of 2015.
But we will have to either do it earlier or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
He estimates that the ruble is now artificially inflated by 10%.
"There is only one way to go", concludes the expert.
But if the Central Bank casts even a shadow of doubt on the financial community that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it could bring the ruble down much more.
