Snowden is willing to "cooperate" with Germany on matters pertaining to U.S. intelligence.
Edward Snowden, the whistleblower of U.S. intelligence, has said that he is willing to travel to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, cannot answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Strebele met with Mr Snowden in Russia, where he has been granted asylum, on Thursday to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: "While the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political speech with criminal charges that offer no protection".
But it's not a crime to tell the truth.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believed that the support of the international community could convince the U.S. government to drop the criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany's interior minister, told Zeit Online: "If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make it possible".
Relations between the US and Germany have become strained following allegations that the NSA has been tapping the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Opperman, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing intelligence, said that if there is an opportunity to hear Mr Snowden as a witness "without putting him in danger and without destroying relations with the US completely", it should be used.
Mr. Ströbele, a member of parliament for the German Green Party, posted a photo of himself with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Strobel said that according to the lawyer of the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not have returned to Russia if he had left.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need assurances that he would be "safe" there, the MP said.
Mr. Snowden said in his letter that he faced a "harsh and persistent" campaign of harassment that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the global reaction to his political statements.
Citizens around the world, as well as high-level officials - including in the United States - have found it socially useful to expose the rampant surveillance system.
The letter offers to cooperate with the German authorities "when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved".
Frontier Airlines will charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for bringing hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, though their announcement on Wednesday said passengers could keep the whole can.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said they'd charge $25 if the fare is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers pay only when they're at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee should make passengers take care of paying in advance.
"We don't want to charge for it", she said.
Airlines began charging for first and second baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these fees stuff as much as they can into the hand luggage that is stored in the upper luggage compartments, often leaving them empty.
Charges are one way to make passengers carry less.
O'Malley said this new collection wasn't really about making money.
The fact is, Frontier's most loyal customers say it's getting harder to find a seat in the upper trunk.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the Frontier check-in line can get a free bag, while the next passenger in the line can pay $100 for the same bag.
O'Malley said the change in procedures on Frontier's website and check-in desks is designed to ensure that passengers are aware of the charge before they reach the gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage fee won't start until the summer, though a date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and that passengers who need the service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most of them did not concern the charges for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand baggage fee three years ago, and another discount Allegiant Air later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungary's Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the hand luggage drive was bringing Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former top executive at Midwest Airlines, recently flew on a Spirit flight and wondered what he would find at the gate when passengers encountered the unusual Spirit handbag collection.
"The boarding process was the smoothest I've seen in my career in the airlines", he said.
I expected to see a grinding of teeth and a fight at the landing.
The plane was full, he said, and the landing was fast.
Frontier also follows Spirit's lead on the $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier stated that passengers who receive a soda or juice can keep the entire can and that a coffee refill will be provided free of charge.
She'll still give out free water.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008, but abandoned it seven months later after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed its lead.
Frontier's initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest move to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers such as Orbitz between $10 and $25 for every ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them rather than going to an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone further than anyone else in this area.
In September, it began giving twice the frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut her mileage premium to 25 percent of her mileage.
So, a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier purchased from an online travel agency would get you 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can only choose a seat in advance if they buy tickets directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and losing money.
Revenue was down 9 percent, and flight capacity was down nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
The NSA blames an "internal error" and not the hackers for the shutdown
The shrouded in secrecy National Security Agency said Friday night that the shutdown of their website for several hours was caused by a technical malfunction, not hackers, as claimed online.
"NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours this evening due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update", the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The claims that the outage was caused by a distributed denial of service attack are not true.
Earlier tonight, online server monitoring systems recorded that the NSA website was down for at least six hours, and the site remains inaccessible to some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency's internal secret network "was not hacked".
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman said.
At least one online hacker activist group has claimed responsibility for taking down the NSA website with a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to flood the targeted website with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site goes down.
The hackers' tactics are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The formerly top-secret NSA, once dubbed "No Such Agency", has been in the spotlight and under fire in recent months after a series of revelations about its extensive foreign and domestic surveillance programs -- all in reaction to top-secret NSA files stolen from the agency and leaked by disgruntled former NSA contractor Edward Snowden.
The growing controversy surrounding the agency has led to speculation that today's incident was the result of a deliberate act of hacking.
Bombardier's profits are falling with the drop in deliveries and orders for planes.
Bombardier, the Canadian manufacturer of airplanes and trains, reported a 15 percent net profit decline on Thursday, driven by lower orders and deliveries of airplanes in the third quarter and contract problems in its railway division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not released any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft and has not provided new information on whether its ambitious plans to bring the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be met.
Since the first test flight of the aircraft about a month and a half ago, it has only flown three more times, raising questions about whether the test phase is on schedule.
The results were not what the forecasts predicted and led to a drop of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his valuation from above-market to mid-market on Thursday, believing that equity growth is limited to the next quarter or two.
"Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the profit figures for the transport department", said Doerksen in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we anticipate that the market will become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes the CSeries family will allow it to gain a foothold in the lower-priced segment of the market, which is currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and first flew in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries are not yet too high, as potential buyers are waiting for flight test results to verify the company's claims about the fuel efficiency and potential economics of the new liner.
There are 403 orders and agreements with 15 clients and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, the leaders also assured analysts and media that the program is moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the plane did not stay on the ground longer than expected", Boduan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the plane's downtime.
All manufacturers plan their tests differently.
We decided to hold the first flight and take a break for updates, which we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks, with all the others to follow shortly, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical of the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it was assessing the operational timing and would provide new information in the next few months.
"This slow pace of flight testing - although apparently in line with Bombardier's internal schedule - reinforces our view that the commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015", Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same at 9 cents.
Gross revenue declined slightly from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected a profit of 10 cents a share and a gross profit of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer reported that it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders dropped from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace department's order book was $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
"In the aerospace sector, the results were in line with our objectives, but the low number of incoming orders and general market conditions were a disadvantage", said Baudouin.
Gross revenue from the aerospace segment fell 13 percent to $2 billion .
Bombardier, the world's largest train manufacturer, reported that gross revenue in this sector increased by almost 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The order book in the transportation unit stood at $32.6 billion as of September 30, slightly above the December 31 figure.
The revenue of the transportation division was negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
Management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares in Bombardier, which also announced that Google CFO Patrick Pichett will join its board, fell 8.5 percent to S$4.83 in mid-Thursday trading.
Brazil's Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and the closest competitor to Bombardier, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
Sony expects lower annual profit
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony Corporation, which ended the quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, has cut its profit forecast for the current fiscal year.
Sony's results for the period from July to September 2013 were more disappointing than expected, due to a drop in demand for TVs, cameras and personal computers produced by the Japanese corporation.
Sony's TV business, which brought the company its first operating profit in three years in the second quarter of the year at ¥5.2 billion, fell again to ¥9.3 billion in operating loss in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through a difficult time, especially due to the decline in demand for TVs.
And while competitors are looking for a way out of this difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
For example, one of Sony's main rivals, Panasonic Corporation, has recently shifted its focus to industrial components: here the company's sales are growing at a high rate, especially due to automotive systems and environmentally friendly technologies.
As a result, by the end of the fiscal year, which ends in March 2014, Sony expects to have a net operating profit of ¥179 billion, up from ¥230 billion previously expected.
According to Thomson Reuters, analysts had expected the figure to be much higher, at 221 billion yen.
In an effort to recover from the crisis, Sony is expanding its product line.
In mid-July, a Japanese company announced the launch of a smartwatch with a number of fashionable features that will make it possible to eliminate the need to take out your smartphone 100 times a day.
