The speech gene was found to stimulate synaptic formation.
Scientists at Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein that makes the "speech gene" Foxp2 function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, and a summary of the study can be found on the journal's website.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
Its role was established in 2001 when a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other was discovered.
The researchers found that the family members had a faulty Foxp2 gene, but the exact way it works was unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that Foxp2 performs at least part of its function as a stimulator of new synapses in the area of the brain associated with speech formation.
It does this because of another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered by searching for factors that stimulate synapse formation.
SXRP2 was one of 10 such genes found by the authors, and Foxp2 is the only one that is activated.
That SRPX2 does indeed affect vocalization has been confirmed by scientists in an experiment on mice.
When the gene activity was artificially reduced in animals, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds it made was restored.
Earlier, a link to the vocalization of Foxp2 itself was also shown in mice.
The animals injected with the human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
However, scientists still do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 controlled by it is associated with purely "mechanical" properties of sound production or more subtle processes.
