The investigation revealed that Ditt had been a "regular Class A drug user" after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on his credit cards.
For eight months, from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two people on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were under police surveillance as part of a wider investigation into the activities of a criminal organisation involved in heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 others were later jailed after police seized £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine in a series of raids, as well as more than £200,000 in cash.
42-year-old Ditta was passing information to criminals for fear that his cocaine addiction would be exposed.
Today at Liverpool Crown Court, Ditta, who works for Blackburn-based law firm Forbes Solicitors, was shamed after pleading guilty to two counts of obstructing justice following a three-week trial at Liverpool Crown Court.
