Why vegetarianism is not suitable for life in Siberia, a RIA Novosti correspondent found out.
People who have completely abandoned animal products should not live in Siberia.
Here, they cannot survive the winter without health losses, and no greenhouse tomatoes compensate them, according to the Novosibirsk dieticians and doctors surveyed on the eve of Vegan Day.
Drinking oil by the liters
Strict vegetarianism, whereby one gives up not only meat and fish but also milk, honey, eggs, is becoming a fashionable way of life.
However, nutritionists are convinced that such strict dietary rules are not good for health in Novosibirsk and other Siberian cities.
Abstaining from animal products is harmful.
Animal proteins contain essential amino acids that are very difficult to replace with plant proteins.
"We have to be sure that we are not eating only milk or eggs", says nutritionist Marina Bogoi.
She cites fish as an example of the essential omega-3 fatty acid.
The most abundant vegetable oil is linseed oil.
"You need to drink a gallon of it to get the amount you need", says a nutritionist.
Doctors believe that Siberians should pay special attention to their diet during the winter.
Vegetarianism is especially in question this season.
The food we eat is highly demanding.
You need a higher calorie intake to keep from freezing.
"If you limit your consumption of animal products, you're not getting enough of these calories", says the expert.
This is the view of nutritionist Olga Pozniak.
She adds that imported fruits and vegetables are not the answer.
It is better to eat food that is grown in the area where you live or where you were born.
The genetic code is tuned to better digest and digest these foods.
And in winter, people don't want to eat cucumbers, but rather hot soup or something more nutritious", explains the doctor.
She says that vegan foods include grains, cereals, legumes, local vegetables, apples left over from winter, and frozen berries.
But that's definitely not enough for a full meal.
According to gastroenterologist Claudia Arifulina, Siberians have their vitamin levels only from mid-August to mid-September.
In our harsh environment, where temperatures can change by 30 degrees a day and snow falls in May, it is not feasible to go completely vegetarian.
The body needs energy to live, and that is primarily fat", says the doctor.
Doctors point out that veganism is especially harmful to children and pregnant women.
Kids grow up, they need building material, including amino acids.
And by being vegetarian, we give them substandard.
Pregnant women also need more protein, vitamins, and trace elements in their diet.
"Vegans don't get it", I swear to God.
Arifulina says that an adult is free to choose whatever he wants, "to play with whatever toys he wants".
He has a fully formed body, skeleton, organs.
And yet, children need to be fed properly.
If parents deprive him of some micronutrient or amino acid by choosing what he eats, it's just a violation of his rights.
"The lack of certain substances for brain, vision, and bone development cannot be repaired tomorrow", she says.
All medical experts surveyed agree that the quality of winter greenhouse and imported vegetables and fruits is poor.
What we get from our farms and grow in greenhouses has less of the micronutrients we need than what we grow in open ground.
"The quality of the products is not that", says Bogoi.
Arifulina also notes that imported and greenhouse vegetables and fruits are far from ideal standards.
Sometimes the desire of the producers to harvest more is detrimental to quality.
"Apples don't turn brown when cut, cucumbers quickly turn yellow and moldy, and tomatoes are tasteless and odorless", he said, adding that they are likely to be over-fertilized.
And they become suppliers of fiber, not vitamins.
