The birds are putting new branches on top, and the bottom layer is already sandwiched between the wires, about to fall.
Of course, it's a pity for the family of storks that nested in the yard every year, raised and fed three or four chicks in the summer, but you don't want to be without light either.
As soon as the birds flew to the warmth of the land, Grandma Anya called the Tsarichansky RES, which owns the stronghold.
I didn't expect them to respond so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest was still holding, - said technical director of DTEK "Dneproplaneurgo" Sergey Berezovsky.
The wires, which were actually already inside the nest, weighing 150 to 200 kilograms, began to corrode.
The birds could have been electrocuted at any moment.
And the locals were at risk of losing power because of the damage to the wires.
So the line installers began a nest rescue operation, not the first time in our practice.
Scientists from the Dnipropetrovsk National University helped, and they developed a scheme for moving the nest.
They've been training the district network staff.
The famous Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised the engineers at all stages of the reconstruction of the nests.
First, it was estimated that there are more than 50 assisted living units in the region.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms were welded, reminiscent of a funnel.
The foundation was covered with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
Experts say that the old branches can be used as a base for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
The vultures will finish their nest by themselves.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka, Novoskovsky District.
Next to the electric pole, a new concrete pillar was erected and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The whole operation cost the power company 9,000 hryvnia.
And the other day, a similar move took place in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, in the courtyard of my grandmother Ani.
Here, the platform was fixed in place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are confident that careful, conservative birds will not even notice that their "apartment" has been overhauled in the spring.
Until the end of the year, the same reconstruction is expected to be carried out in four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichan districts of the Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some people save rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
