News: Obama campaign staff considered removing Biden in favor of Hillary Clinton
The New York Times reported that President Barack Obama's closest advisers were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 ballot.
This is the opening of the most sensational and highly anticipated book on the 2012 campaign by Mark Halperin and John Heilemann, "Doubled the Stakes: The Game Changed 2012".
The Times obtained a copy of the forthcoming book and reported Thursday night that the president's closest aides conducted "large-scale focus group research and public opinion polls in late 2011" to assess whether Biden's ouster could help raise waning hopes for Obama's reelection.
According to The Times political commentator Jonathan Martin, the book details the attempts of senior campaign and White House officials, namely former White House Chief of Staff Bill Daley, to gauge the effect of former Secretary of State Clinton's appointment as vice president on the vote.
The possible replacement was a closely guarded secret in Chicago's campaign headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president's closest advisers - including Daley, former Obama campaign chief Jim Messina, and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Plouffe - knew that the replacement was under consideration.
The book "Double the Stakes" claims that Daly initiated the effort to replace Biden despite their "close personal relationship", but ultimately abandoned the move when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral roll would not significantly improve Obama's chances.
In an interview with Martin, Daley confirmed that the administration was indeed considering a replacement for Biden Clinton.
"I was very vocal about looking at a lot of things, and this was one of them", he told the Daily.
You have to remember that at that moment the president was in terrible shape, so we thought, "Oh my God, what are we going to do?"
While Daley described the study as "a necessary test", Martin told CNN's Anderson Cooper that the campaign has invested heavily in studying whether this move will bring voting dividends.
"Pre-election campaign teams don't spend that kind of money on polls and focus groups unless they are serious about something", Martin told AK360.
It's unclear, however, whether Obama knew his team was looking into a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then-boss knew about the possible mix-up.
Although Daley said he didn't think the president knew about the possible replacement, the former chief of staff admitted that Obama might have known.
Martin added that "Double the Stakes" doesn't provide a clear answer to the question of whether the results of political probing reached Obama's desk.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believed Obama was unaware of the investigation into the possibility of removing Biden from the ballot.
"Maybe", Martin said, "but I'm not sure that's the case.
