Since October 28, the Russian customs authorities have begun to apply additional measures to guarantee the delivery of goods, - said the Deputy head of the Eastern customs Vladimir Denissov.
The new document is used in countries that have joined the convention on international carriage.
The checkpoints are working in high gear.
FACT's correspondent visited the border and talked to the truckers who were held hostage.
Prices in the roadside shop-cafe at the Novoazovsk checkpoint are rising every day, as is the line from the van.
The trucks are lined up in rows, stretching for about a mile [2 km].
The customs terminal Novoazovsk - Veseli-Vozneshenka provides one of the most important transportation directions from the south of Ukraine on the international highway.
From here the cargo is sent to the Stavropol Territory of Russia, Kazakhstan, Georgia, Armenia.
On Sunday, they let us in until midnight, and then they introduced these rules, - complains Alexey Golovanev (pictured), a truck driver who transports cargo from Turkey to Kazakhstan through Russia and has been sleeping in his car for almost a week.
Under the new rules, to cross the border, I need a supplementary package of documents and a cargo insurance payment.
The amount depends on the value of the cargo and the distance it is transported.
The minimum insurance is 4,5-5 thousand rubles (about 1,100-1300 hryvnia).
Those who are going to a nearby place (say, Georgia, Armenia) with cargo worth up to 50 thousand dollars, pay about 15 thousand rubles (3800 hryvnia) and travel.
And the rest of you are stuck, because nobody has that much money on them!
Imagine if a driver were to carry a cargo worth only $4,000, but to get to Moscow, he would need to pay 90,000 rubles (almost 23,000 hryvnia) for transit!
The conditions for survival at the border are nowhere, lament truckers who eat near their cars.
The stores and cafes on the border are always expensive, but we've never seen anything like this!
The vendors quickly got their heads around the price of the bags: 15 hryvnias for a piece of bread, 7 hryvnias for a cup of coffee, 25 hryvnias for a bowl of soup.
And the coffee is one.
And there's no toilet.
We sleep in the steppe, we go to the toilet there.
No washing or shaving...
I can go a week without getting out of the car, my wife has everything ready for the road.
"I'll be here for a week", says another truck driver, Victor Skorarenko, who is trying to console himself.
I wonder if my car will be in line for a week?
We're interested in the only shop on the border.
There are 11 and 15 hryvnia.
What, a crystal bottle or a silver-plated water?
We're a coffee shop, not a store.
"Take it while there's still something", says the saleswoman.
After the situation began to be covered in the media, the plight of Ukrainian drivers drew the attention of the regional authorities.
