I'm more of a scrapbook now.
I haven't been called to give out candy in my apartment for the last two years, and I probably won't be this year.
But the statistics show that I'm a white-washed Halloween crow.
According to the National Retail Federation, most Americans - 158 million - will be celebrating Halloween this year and will spend a total of $6.9 billion on candy, costumes and decorations.
The one thing I look forward to every Halloween is trends.
The National Retail Federation predicts that $1.2 billion of the $6.9 billion spent on costumes will be spent on clothing.
This year, the hot topics are the sexy, uninspired items.
Women no longer have to be sex workers; they can also be sex food, like pizza, hamburgers, or carrots.
As for the men, I think we're going to see a lot of zombies thanks to The Walking Dead, and I'm sure Daft Punk-style astronauts will be in our Instagram feeds this year.
According to Google, the costumes that are searched the most are zombies, Batman, pirates and witches.
I guess there's nothing wrong with the traditional approach.
We dressed our dogs last year, and to my surprise, we weren't the only ones.
In fact, according to the National Retail Federation, Americans will spend $330 million on pet suits this year.
That means a lot of funny dog-dogs.
When it comes to candy, we don't cut corners.
Americans will spend $1.9 billion on them this year, according to Nielsen.
That's about 600 million pounds of Hershey's chocolate, candy, Milk Duds, chewy Twizzlers and the Clark Bar candy bars.
