George Carevan: the break with Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the European Free Movement Area as a condition of EU membership.
There's a series of stories about passport control in Berwick and the barbed wire border along the Adrianow ramp.
True, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of more free movement across the rest of Europe, although  predictably  it did not appear in the headlines.
Nor has anyone pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time twisting their formal rules to suit their own convenience.
Since Scotland is now outside the Schengen area, continuing to flout the requirements would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for what it really wanted from the Scots.
So it's not a story worth telling.
And so old that it's become a fossil: I first heard the joke that "independence is passport control" at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting point lost in retelling the old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey Europe's orders at all?
Why trade London's yoke for Brussels' yoke, especially now?
Here's the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or in favor of abolishing the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded just this year, emerged from nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (analogous to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has been a watershed moment.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles placed on national economies through the maintenance of the single currency, have led many people to think that the 'Europe' project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits, and that was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has locked its members into exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, southern Europe is already at a disadvantage in terms of production potential compared with Germany.
The only lifeline is to cut salaries and public spending, which Berlin is actively supporting.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper problem of Europe's productive capacity.
As a result of the package of 'green' energy measures introduced by Brussels, a 'code' that means subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the US.
It's a paralyzingly unfavorable price situation, as we've seen before in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze anywhere in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
The result is a riot brewing, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needed Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and had already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France's shattered economy in a mess.
The result is that the right-wing, anti-EU Marine Le Pen party, the National Front, has just won a decisive by-election, knocking the ruling Socialist Party into third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote a timely warning to British Labour that it is not possible to assume that a split in the right will automatically be reflected in the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If - and this is very likely - anti-EU parties win support in these elections, the bloc could for the first time take a dominant position in the European Parliament.
My view is that soon the growing anti-EU and anti-single currency sentiment in Europe will come together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to the sort of vague "Europe of nations" that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and a few dependent economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I suspect the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to draw closer to the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests the possibility that Britain will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
What position does that leave Scotland in?
We can choose to be a region of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can protect our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland can thrive in a freer European arrangement, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating the Norwegian experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is  oddly  the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity, having won an impressive majority of votes in 2011 thanks to objections to the spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Liberal Democrat coalition.
It would be absurd for Scotland to vote for independence now just to accept austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: aging before the age of puberty
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, studies show.
Physical changes don't mean puberty is near.
There's no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty.
The tendency to early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter's breast and pubic hair begin to form at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual meeting of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent the new normal.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents", Kaplowitz said, "but that doesn't usually mean full puberty is coming soon".
Obvious signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic and arthritic hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there's been only a small shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 years in 1970.
"After the breasts start to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the menarche", said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early puberty in girls: how to deal with this common problem".
Time is the most accurate way to check how puberty will progress.
There is debate about what constitutes actual puberty, but it is considered "premature" when breast enlargement is accompanied by a sharp increase in height until the age of 8.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression may warrant tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems, such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone ageing, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and poor growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, developmental level, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is cautious about medication, but admits that "suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers".
The other big problem is obvious: parents just don't want their very young daughters to have their period.
"They are worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle the hygiene issues", said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock", recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating when she was 10 years old.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many widely publicized theories about the causes of premature puberty.
Yet, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, environmental chemicals, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Both boys and girls reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the premise that holds the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of 6- to 9-year-old girls that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty appears to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency toward full puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
Even infants and toddlers are prone to acne and pubic hair.
"We have to be careful about how we define true puberty", said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goryea Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not feel uncomfortable asking their pediatrician for guidance on how to talk to their child.
"This could mean an earlier than expected conversation", Kaplowitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need to be reassured that even when it happens before their due time, it's a normal part of life.
