A new nicotine vaccine may make smoking less fun
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could make smoking a pleasure-free experience.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mice from lifelong nicotine dependence.
More tests are needed before human trials can begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the early results are encouraging.
"We are very hopeful that this vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried all the methods available on the market today to quit, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to be overcome with these modern tools", said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry the genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests, vaccinated mice who were subsequently given nicotine continued their normal activities.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine were "relaxed", a sign that nicotine had reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain high levels of antibodies, injections had to be done so frequently that they were expensive and impractical.
But the new vaccine will probably cost much less because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if a future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have the urge to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it's more likely to be used by smokers to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get the pleasure from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that may help them to get rid of the habit", he said.
