Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia  where household debt is rising  is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its business, became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
A jewelry loan  is not only a quick way to get money (S$1300 in the case of Mrs. Amirthaling), but it is almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17%, slightly above the 15.4% offered by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, the advantage of the pawnshop is that it does not require credit checks or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
So millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel the pressure of rising living costs and the rapid growth of household and consumer debt.
After five years of steady growth following the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by loose monetary policies in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to compensate for diminishing incomes as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor's, the rating agency, pointed to the increase in household credit, largely due to the growth in mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week barely emerged from a technical recession.
Thursday's data showed continued decline in exports and weaker consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising prices, people in the middle and lower [income brackets] will look for ways to supplement their income wherever they can", says Song Seung Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the past two years have increased the rush with which people pawn their personal belongings as they take the opportunity to cash in on their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the items pawned at the city-state's 200 pawn shops are gold items.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month".
In Thailand, EasyMoney, the largest operator of pawnshops, has seen a rise in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
