Scientists have shed light on how a dog's tail movements are linked to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs wag their tails to the right (from the dog's perspective), while anxious dogs wag their tails predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the canine family can detect these subtle differences in tail wagging and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Valortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: "It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain are involved in the formation of the stimuli that produce positive and negative emotions in different people".
Here we've tried to look at this in other species.
He added that just as in humans, the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the tail wagging of other dogs, researchers observed the animals as they watched films about other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rates and analyzed their behavior.
We may soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, "We showed the dogs the dog videos, either the naturalistic versions or the silhouette, to get rid of any other distortion factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and point the tail more to the left or to the right".
When the animals saw that the otherwise unresponsive dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the tail-waving dog), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was tilted predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of a wagging tail dog), their heartbeat increased and they looked worried.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that the dogs were intentionally communicating with each other by these gestures.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they should worry about and which ones they shouldn't.
He notes: "If there are several encounters with other dogs and their tail wagging in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side produces less friendly behavior, then the dog responds based on this experience".
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animals' emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting research fellow at Bristol University's veterinary school, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a team of researchers at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads left when they see an aggressive dog, and right when they see a contented dog.
And in another study from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported that "Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when their tail was turned left instead of right, rather than becoming agitated, the opposite of the Italian study".
He said that the differences could be because the dogs in the different studies didn't fully perceive the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
It might be useful to study how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is ample evidence in different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception", he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it's likely that we'll soon understand why their tails sometimes point one way and sometimes the other.
