GM is recalling a number of new pickups in the U.S. for reworking the backs of the seats.
General Motors Co is recalling nearly 19,000 brand new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickups to address issues with manual seatback tilt, according to a notice from U.S. vehicle safety regulators filed Friday.
On some of the pickups, the front seats may have a defect in the backrest tilt mechanism.
As a result, the seat backs do not meet federal vehicle safety standards for head restraints.
"In a rear-end collision, a helmet may not adequately protect the driver and passengers, increasing the risk of injury", says a notice posted on the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration website.
The recalled models were manufactured between August 1 and September 10.
GM's pickup truck launch in June is the most important vehicle launch for the leading American automaker since its 2009 bankruptcy restructuring.
GM notified the pickup truck owners of the defect in the first half of October.
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration could not consider a notice to owners due to the 16-day government shutdown that slowed car sales growth in October.
Sales of the Silverado and Sierra pickups, which were upgraded for the 2014 model lineup, rose by about 20 percent during the first 10 months of this year, GM said Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickups and 16,503 Sierra pickups, which were the highest ever sales.
GM's shares on the New York Stock Exchange rose 1.4 percent to $37.47 on Friday afternoon.
The cry of despair of the Obama voter
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope of change.
He says Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to undermine commendable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify the problems with the website of Obama's health care reform, the drone attacks.
The memoirs of the 2008 Obama campaign are a sad reminder of what could have been.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard University.
I'm reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would lift me up during my downtime in second year medical school and give me a new sense of hope.
It's called "Courage to Win", and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing my patient reports in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speaking could take your breath away.
The election was a resounding victory, and the news anchors paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents saved every newspaper they could find.
A young team of strategists was about to arrive at the White House, and the people were ready for a change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his approval rating was 82 percent.
Then I close the book.
Coming back to the present is a rude awakening, like being plucked from a dream.
It's hard to recall those days of optimism, they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my ballot, change has indeed occurred.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I give Obama credit for his many and varied accomplishments, from passing the Affordable Care Act to pulling our troops out of Iraq, repealing the Don't Ask, Don't Tell policy, killing Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the ability to choose public health care, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay among others.
But after countless times I've sided with the Obama administration, defending it to colleagues and peers, I'm running out of explanations to offer.
I've reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain the permission to bug foreign leaders or the drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
It cannot explain the NSA's collection of Americans' private information or the prosecution of whistleblowers who expose government wrongdoing.
It cannot explain the murder of American citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial and investigation or the failure to respect public funding and spending limits during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the report's conclusion that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive since the Nixon administration".
And lately, he can't justify not being able to develop a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Was I supposed to understand at the age of 18 that leadership could be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it?
It's clear that running for elected office is not a predictable agenda, as our public dialogue will be shaped by the opposition political party and by random events like the Newtown massacre.
However, all of the examples I've listed above show that they were largely the administration's own choices.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a vague and crude alternative, seemingly incapable of making a decision about his own politics or beliefs.
I thought that in his second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of the next election, would live up to the expectations we've been hearing about for so long.
However, with Obama's approval rating dropping below 45% this week, going back to 2008 with this book has become much harder.
It makes me miss a lot of promises that have gone unfulfilled.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton handed Obama a roaring defeat in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a meeting to analyze the causes of the failure, he told his staff that they should get back on track and stay true to their purpose.
"I want us to be attractive again", he said.
We must remember who we are.
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I agree with you completely.
The views expressed in this commentary are those of Nathaniel Morris alone.
