RBS suspends two currency traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has temporarily suspended two traders from its currency trading unit, according to two people familiar with the situation, further evidence that a global probe by regulators into alleged currency manipulation is gaining momentum.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in investigations related to the world's largest financial market, with a daily turnover of $5.3 trillion.
These two traders will be the first RBS employees to be removed in the course of an ongoing investigation that echoes the LIBOR manipulation scandal.
Refusing to comment on the suspension, the bank confirmed that it had received information requests from regulators this month.
"Our ongoing investigation of this matter is ongoing, and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other regulators", the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people familiar with the matter said that RBS had passed on the records of emails and instant messages that its former trader had received and sent to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Asher, left RBS in 2010 and, as far as we know, is on leave from his current position as head of European spot foreign exchange trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, went on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr. Asher's IM contact group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to people familiar with the matter.
UBS Bank announced this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating alleged currency market manipulation at a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulatory bodies worldwide - the European Commission, Finma, Swiss antitrust body Weko, FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are looking into allegations that bankers colluded to influence the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, said people familiar with the situation.
Banks are looking through instant messages and e-mails for years looking for cases of wrongdoing.
The news of the inspections has alarmed traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest sources of revenue for investment bank trading units in recent years, but has been hit hard this year as low currency volatility has reduced opportunities for buyers.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the seriousness of the situation by saying that a vast and highly liquid currency market is virtually impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say that's not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily trading in the forex market, the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the wider use of banks of their internal platforms means that "you can start to influence the market for a very small price".
The news comes on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it was firing one of its London Stock Exchange trading desk this week after causing a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The bank has notified the relevant authorities immediately and is cooperating with its regulators.
"We believe that the trader acted alone and that the matter was localized", Credit Suisse said.
