Egypt's first freely elected president takes oath
Mohammed Morsi is sworn in, but the day of his inauguration is unlikely to mark the end of political strife in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Mohammed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he took the oath as the country's first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was deposed 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president in the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before 18 judges in black robes in a courthouse on the banks of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are seeking a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic", Morsi said during a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
"Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations of a new life of absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability", said Morsi, a 60-year-old American-educated engineer from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that for most of its 84 years of existence was a banned organization, a target for the tough actions of successive governments.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and police when Morsi arrived with a small motorcade shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to welcome the new president, and, unlike the presidential pump of Mubarak's time, traffic was stopped only briefly to allow his motorcade to pass along the usually busy road connecting the city centre to the southern suburbs.
Although Morsi has been derided as the uncharismatic "spare wheel" of the "Brothers", his personal prestige has risen sharply since his victory and Friday's speech in which he tried to present himself as the candidate of not only Islamists but all those who want to bring to an end the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state today", Morsi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red tie, told the judges in the wood-paneled courtroom where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University, where he was to deliver his inaugural address.
He was given an official reception with an army orchestra playing the national anthem, during which he stood on the "smirno" stand.
The military man was present, Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi.
His arrival was greeted by the slogan "Army and people are one", which was chanted by hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Founded in 1908 as a stronghold of secular education, Cairo University became a stronghold of Islamist student groups in the 1970s.
Morsi took the symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, where the uprising that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year began, and promised to restore the powers of the president that were stripped from him by the military council that took over from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take the oath before a court rather than parliament, as is customary, he is fulfilling the will of the military, and this is a sign that the struggle for power will continue.
Morsi's speech in Tahrir Square was filled with theatrical populist gestures.
