Traveling through mud, rivers and jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bvelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Blewell and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients
In this West African country, there are not many doctors  just one for every 5,000 people
Vote here or on your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bvellet is one of the top 10 CNN heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 heroes to be CNN Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bvellet watched his father come back to life and fall into a state of unconsciousness again, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bvellet was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to his brain and caused a hematoma that would haunt him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon", Georges Bulle said.
If we had money, we'd get him out of Cameroon.
Instead, for years, Bvellet accompanied his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
"It's not easy", said Bvelle.
You can leave your house at 5 in the morning, run to the hospital to be the first, but you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people may die because of having to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Father Bevelle died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one doctor for every 5,000 people.
In comparison, the United States has one doctor for every 413 people.
And even if they could afford to see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the health care spending in this country is private.
"Their only problem is poverty", said Bvellet.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy their lives.
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his countrymen, Bvelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bvellet and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend trips to rural areas to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his team of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others pile into the vans, tie medical supplies to the roofs, and drive through the rough terrain to visit villages in need.
They don't always have the luck.
They had to push their cars through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as heroes: a celebration of song and dance and the finest facilities the locals have to offer.
The free health care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bjelle, with his wide smile and boundless energy, is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to take in hundreds of patients.
"We take 500 people on each trip", Bvelle said.
They come from all over the county within a 40-mile radius of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these day-care centres provides a variety of healthcare services.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get cribs, donated glasses, or free birth certificates or school-related documents that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
The surgery is usually performed in a school, a municipal building or at home; after the procedure, the patient stands up and walks to the post-operative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating and sanitary equipment, Bvelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It's an unbearable pace, but the dedication of the band usually helps to support the village musicians.
"They beat the drums all night long to keep us awake and keep us working", said Bjelle.
On Sunday, the team members head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This team of doctors from Cameroon and international medical students have performed 700 free surgeries in the past year, and they know that their help can mean a lot to the people they help.
One man explained that his free operation to treat his hernia would enable him to work again.
"This will change the future for me and my family", the man said.
In addition to these clinical appointments on weekends and work at the hospital, surgeon Bvelle also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
This second work, he says, provides 60 percent of the funding for his nonprofit organization; the rest comes from private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping", said Kathy O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, who volunteers with the Bvella group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that we can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses like O'Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe to join Buewell in his work, it's a practice opportunity they would never have had back home.
"We were able to assist in surgeries, where we helped remove blood stains or held instruments for Dr. Bwelle", O'Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Student volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medication.
But when they arrive in Yaoundé, it is Bvella who pays for their food, transportation, and education.
"He's a hero, without a doubt", said O'Malley.
He has devoted his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Blevelle, the almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is what brings him the greatest joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job", said Bevelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh, to make their pain less.
Go to ASCOVIME and see what you can do to help.
