Rosbalt agency stripped of media status for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court ruled that the license to register the agency "Rosbalt" was invalid, "Lenta" writes.
The agency was stripped of its media status by Roskomnadzor for systematic and gross violations of the media law.
The trial set an unpleasant precedent: the court found it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to raise counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"?
JSC "Rosbalt Information Agency" was founded in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In subsequent years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, "Rosbalt" has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was among the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement bodies.
The publication's close relationship to the security services has been discussed throughout the agency's existence.
In addition to the fact that "Rosbalt" had a large database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions spoke the fact that the head of the project was Natalia Chaplin - the wife of Victor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplin's role in the management of "Rosbalt" is not entirely clear: most often she is called "the head of the project".
The agency's director general is Larisa Afonina, and the editor in chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Rosbalt has not been ranked by the federal media recently, not in terms of citation, not in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took 25th place in the ranking of visited sites of Russian media according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes on the Kremlin's impotence in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and joke", pogroms in the capital city of Biryulev.
The conflict between Roskomnadzor and Rosbalt began in July 2013, when amendments to the media law prohibited journalists from uttering uncensored profanity.
The agency found banned language in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil towers").
The sides describe the aftermath in different ways.
Roskomnadzor, based on the found footage, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the media law and asked the court to revoke the agency's license.
Rosbalt claimed that the claims of the agency were illegitimate: first, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
The agency representatives appealed Roskomnadzor's claims to the world court - and when the Moscow City Court accepted Roskomnadzor's claim on October 22, 2013, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th, the world judge decided against Rosbalt: the chief editor Nikolay Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offenses and was fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this was the outcome of the Mosgorsk trial - if you give up the idea that the outcome could have been decided even earlier.
On October 31, the court ruled that the Rosbalt registration certificate was invalid, effectively depriving the agency of its media status.
It's not like Rosbalt was alone in this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by the deputies of the State Duma (the application to the head of the Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted on the initiative of the CPRF).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov declared the publication's closure illegal.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the Roskomnadzor leadership even gave him some guarantees that the case would not reach the revocation of the license.
The Rosbalt trial showed that the question of whose jurisdiction is safer for the media in Russia today is a big one.
