Australian woman appeals against prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming she was attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on June 15 by the Phuket Provincial Court of filing a false claim after the Thai police reported that a local taxi driver had attacked her on the night of Sunday, June 10, while two other men were holding her.
However, CCTV footage later revealed that she had returned safely to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Bamford was questioned by Phuket police for two days before she confessed to fabricating the story.
She was held in local police cells until the trial.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a general-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, not an adult women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told Sydney's Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "very concerned" about their daughter's well-being and were waiting for her return to Australia.
"Obviously it was a very worrying time, but we hope she gets home safely as soon as possible", Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on 50,000 baht bail.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the Krabi resort area in southern Thailand.
Thai-based legal sources said Bamford is currently represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that an appeal could see the court increase her sentence by up to two years and force her to serve time in an adult prison.
However, following the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michel Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to rebuild its damaged tourist image, leading to an acquittal.
